<hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/654"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_654_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=2ac8d9a1f385979e418af28d9242a328&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Jeremy Baumberg" border="0" width="120" height="78" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/654">Nanotechnology expert honoured by Royal Society</a></h3><p>Professor Jeremy Baumberg is this year's winner of the Royal Society's prestigious Mullard Award. The award has been made to Professor Baumberg for his work in nanoscience and nanotechnology and for his contribution to the national prosperity of the UK through the University's spin-out company Mesophotonics Ltd in developing optical chips.  He will receive his award from Paul Boateng MP, Chief Secretary to the Treasury on Monday 29 November at a Royal Society dinner.</p><p></p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/650"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_650_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=6af2d7e945ad2a050cf5f399ab499ed3&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="" border="0" width="118" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/650">Revolutionising breast cancer treatment through knowledge management</a></h3><p>UK scientists have designed a knowledge management system which could enable medical practitioners to make speedy, informed decisions about breast cancer patients. The project pulls together information which was previously held in separate locations and it has the potential to revolutionise patient diagnosis and management.</p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_648_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=79f1f98268f0d095c6a238ab630302b4&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="" border="0" width="120" height="90" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3>Hot response to ECS/ORC fire drill</h3><p>Staff from Mountbatten Clean Rooms were among several hundred people evacuated from Zepler and Mountbatten Buildings this morning in the annual ECS/ORC Annual Fire Drill. The evacuation was assisted by members of the University's Security Service. According to John Tucknott, Safety Co-ordinator, the event was useful in identifying areas where higher safety awareness is needed from staff in both buildings.</p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/645">Conference reviews design of complex electronic systems</a></h3><p>To meet the UK's massive demand for mobile communications it is essential for designers and programmers to work more closely together. This is the premise of the UK's first Electronic Design Automation (EDA) Tools Forum, which is being held at the Institution of Electrical Engineers on Tuesday 16 and Wednesday 17 November, to review the tools used to design today's complex semiconductors and electronic systems.</p><p>The EDA Tools Forum is co-organised and chaired by Professor Bashir Al-Hashimi of the School of Electronics and Computer Science.</p></div><p class="clearBoth"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20041208102135/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/">More News</a></p><br style="clear: both;" />
